Add JWT auth for the admin panel

Replace the client-side `admin / admin123` mock with real authentication
backed by Spring Security + JWT.

Backend:
- New `auth/` package: `AdminUser` JPA entity, repository,
  `AdminUserDetailsService`, `JwtService`, `JwtAuthFilter`, `AuthController`
  (`POST /api/auth/login`, `GET /api/auth/me`), and a `SecurityConfig`
  that wires it all together. Stateless, BCrypt password hashes, HS512
  signed tokens.
- `SecurityConfig` allows public reads on `/api/articles`,
  `/api/upcoming-projects`, `/api/completed-projects`, `/api/comments/**`,
  the public form submissions (`POST /api/volunteers`, donation flow),
  Stripe callbacks, `/uploads/**`, and `/api/auth/**`. Anything else
  under `/api/**` requires `ROLE_ADMIN`.
- CORS moves out of `WebConfig` and into a configurable
  `CorsConfigurationSource` driven by `CORS_ALLOWED_ORIGINS`. Production
  deploys add the Netlify hostnames here.
- `AdminBootstrap` `ApplicationRunner` seeds one admin user from
  `ADMIN_BOOTSTRAP_USERNAME` / `ADMIN_BOOTSTRAP_PASSWORD` if (and only
  if) the `admin_users` table is empty. Once one exists, those env vars
  are ignored.
- `application.properties`, `.env`, `.env.example` and `docker-compose.yml`
  gain `JWT_SECRET`, `JWT_EXPIRATION_MS`, `CORS_ALLOWED_ORIGINS` and the
  bootstrap admin variables.

Frontend (admin):
- New `services/auth.js` with `login` / `logout` / `verifyToken` and an
  `authFetch` wrapper that auto-attaches the bearer token and clears
  local state on 401.
- `Login.jsx` calls `POST /api/auth/login` and surfaces server errors.
- `App.js` checks the stored token on mount, shows a "checking session"
  state while it verifies, and persists login across page reloads.
- `Articles`, `Volunteers`, `UpcomingProjects`, `CompletedProjects`, and
  `services/api.js` swap bare `fetch` for `authFetch`.

The default dev credentials are `admin / changeme` (set in `.env`).
Rotate before going public.
